element.definition: Logical model for Problem
Unique identifier of the problem
Date of last modification of the information by the recorder

extension.valueString: Date de la dernire modification des informations par l'enregistreur
Datum van laatste wijziging van de informatie door de recorder

element.definition: The healthcare professional responsible for the content (ideally identified by the NISS)

extension.valueString: Le professionnel de la sant responsable du contenu (idalement identifi par le NISS)
De zorgprofessional die verantwoordelijk is voor de inhoud (idealiter gedentificeerd door de NISS)

element.definition: The person asserting the information (e.g., patient, practitioner, parent; ideally identified by the NISS)

extension.valueString: La personne qui revendique l'information (par exemple, le patient, le praticien, le parent ; idalement identifie par le NISS).
De persoon die de informatie bevestigt (bijv. patint, behandelaar, ouder; idealiter gedentificeerd door het NISS)

element.definition: Reference or Identifier to the patient (ideally identified by the NISS)

extension.valueString: Rfrence ou identifiant du patient (idalement identifi par le NISS)
Referentie of identificator van de patint (idealiter gedentificeerd door het NISS)

element.definition: Reference to the primary cause of the problem (procedure, medication administration, or other condition)

extension.valueString: Rfrence  la cause premire du problme (procdure, administration de mdicaments ou autre condition)
Verwijzing naar de primaire oorzaak van het probleem (procedure, toediening van medicatie of andere aandoening)

element.definition: Thematic category of the problem
Identification of the problem - in SNOMED-CT

extension.valueString: Identificatie van het probleem - in SNOMED-CT

element.definition: Clinical status of the problem (active, inactive, resolved, etc.)

extension.valueString: Statut clinique du problme (actif, inactif, rsolu, etc.)
Klinische status van het probleem (actief, inactief, opgelost, enz.)

element.definition: Degree of certainty associated with the problem (confirmed, suspected, etc.)

extension.valueString: Degr de certitude associ au problme (confirm, suspect, etc.)
Mate van zekerheid over het probleem (bevestigd, vermoed, enz.)

element.definition: Course of disease evolution (acute, chronic, fulminant, etc.)

extension.valueString: volution de la maladie (aigu, chronique, fulminante, etc.)
Verloop van de ziekte-evolutie (acuut, chronisch, fulminant, etc.)

element.definition: Symptoms recorded in the context of this problem

extension.valueString: Symptmes enregistrs dans le cadre de ce problme
Symptomen opgenomen in de context van dit probleem

element.definition: Degree of severity of the problem

extension.valueString: Mate van ernst van het probleem

element.definition: Anatomical site(s) where the problem is active

Anatomische plaats(en) waar het probleem actief is

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

slicing.description: Extensions are always sliced by (at least) url

element.definition: May be used to represent additional information that is not part of the basic definition of the element. To make the use of extensions safe and manageable, there is a strict set of governance  applied to the definition and use of extensions. Though any implementer can define an extension, there is a set of requirements that SHALL be met as part of the definition of the extension.
element.comment: There can be no stigma associated with the use of extensions by any application, project, or standard - regardless of the institution or jurisdiction that uses or defines the extensions.  The use of extensions is what allows the FHIR specification to retain a core level of simplicity for everyone.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children
Must have either extensions or value[x], not both

element.short: Code defined by a terminology system
element.definition: A reference to a code defined by a terminology system.
element.comment: Codes may be defined very casually in enumerations, or code lists, up to very formal definitions such as SNOMED CT - see the HL7 v3 Core Principles for more information.  Ordering of codings is undefined and SHALL NOT be used to infer meaning. Generally, at most only one of the coding values will be labeled as UserSelected = true.
element.requirements: Allows for alternative encodings within a code system, and translations to other code systems.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.short: Plain text representation of the concept
element.definition: A human language representation of the concept as seen/selected/uttered by the user who entered the data and/or which represents the intended meaning of the user.
element.comment: Very often the text is the same as a displayName of one of the codings.
element.requirements: The codes from the terminologies do not always capture the correct meaning with all the nuances of the human using them, or sometimes there is no appropriate code at all. In these cases, the text is used to capture the full meaning of the source.
